For planning purposes, Regency has considered the impact of a "worst case" accident, defined to be a complete release from the 35,000 gallon tank, resulting in the instantaneous formation of a vapor cloud which explodes. Using the EPA OCA Guidance Equations, a potential radius of impact due to the explosion was calculated to extend to 0.44 miles. Global positioning system (GPS) locations were gathered on surrounding area residences that could conceivably fall into the worst case catastrophic event, and it was determined that there were none within a 1 mile radius of the tank. It should be emphasized that the probability of the worst-case catastrophic event evaluated in this report is extremely remote - far less than natural catastrophes such as tornadoes and floods that could produce much more severe and extensive damage and injury. A consideration of the 0.44 mile radius has been incorporated into our notification and emergency response planning.

Regency has implemented safety precautions and procedures designed to prevent and mitigate catastrophic releases. Regency has active operating, maintenance, training, and inspection procedures. Regency provides annual emergency response training to its employees. In addition, Regency will coordinate with local emergency responders, including the Eagle Pass Fire Department and the Local Emergency Planning Committee. The Eagle Pass Gas Processing Plant is currently under construction and all facility-specific training of employees and responders will be completed before operation is initiated.

Regency's management is committed to the following:
-Preventing accidents;
-Training our employees in correct response procedures in the event of an accident;
-Participating in community emergency preparedness;
-Addressing any citizen concerns by fully explaining potential hazards associated with Regency operations and all steps being taken to prevent and mitigate accidents;
